<div class="social-comment-inner social-clearfix" id="comment-83">
	<div class="social-comment-header">
		<div class="social-comment-author ">
			<img alt='' src='http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/?s=40&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/?s=80&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-40 photo avatar-default' height='40' width='40' /><cite class="social-fn fn">AJ Carey</cite>		</div>
		<!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
		<div class="social-comment-meta social-comment-meta-wordpress">
			<span class="social-posted-from">
								<span>View</span>
							</span>
			<a href="http://werblog.com/2006/04/the-beeb/#comment-83" class="social-posted-when" target="_blank">April 12, 2006</a>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="social-comment-body">
				<p>I find telecom policy in other countries particularly fascinating and especially those in England and its former colonies like Canada and New Zealand. Part of what intrigues me is their undying faith in the power of government to &#8220;fix&#8221; things. I just don&#8217;t get it. Almost every example of government regulation in the United States has been a case study in failure. I think that it would be the case for net neutrality as well. The free market is generally a much more successful venue.</p>
	</div>
